= History of Shirk (Polytheism)

== The foundation:

Tawḥīd (Monotheism) is the original foundation among the children of Ādam, while
shirk (polytheism) came later and was not part of the original belief. Ibn
ʿAbbās said #pleasedHIM : “Between Ādam and Nūḥ were ten generations, all upon
Tawḥīd.”

== The first occurrence of shirk on Earth:

It began among the people of Nūḥ, when they exaggerated the status of righteous
men. They made images of them for remembrance, which eventually led to
worshipping them besides Allāh. So Allāh sent Nūḥ #salamHIM to call them back to
pure monotheism.

== Shirk among the people of Mūsā #salamHIM:

It occurred when they took the calf as an idol for worship.

== Shirk among the Christians (Nasārā):

It occurred after ʿIsā #salamHIM was raised to the heavens. A man named Paul,
who pretended to believe in Christ but intended to corrupt the religion,
introduced the belief in the Trinity, the worship of the cross, and many pagan
elements.

== Shirk among the Arabs:

It was introduced by ʿAmr ibn Luhayy Al-Khuzāʾi, who altered the religion of
Ibrāhīm #salamHIM and brought idols to the land of Ḥijāz, commanding the people
to worship them.

== Shirk in the Ummah of Muḥammad #pbuh:

Appeared after the fourth Hijri century through the Fāṭimid Shia, who built
shrines over graves, introduced the innovation of celebrating birthdays of the
Prophet (Mawālid), and exaggerated the status of the righteous.

It also spread with the rise of deviant Sufism, marked by excessive
glorification of spiritual leaders (_mashāyikh_) and followers of mystical paths
(_ṭuruq_) which lead some to seek blessings and help from them instead of Allāh.)